    rationaleLong: "Button battery impaction in the esophagus is a time-critical emergency. Button batteries lodged in the esophagus can cause tissue necrosis, perforation, and fatal hemorrhage in as little as 2 hours through an electrochemical mechanism. The battery generates an external current that hydrolyzes tissue fluids, producing hydroxide ions (alkaline burns) at the negative pole. This causes liquefactive necrosis that can erode through the esophageal wall into adjacent structures including the aorta (causing fatal aortoesophageal fistula), trachea (tracheoesophageal fistula), or mediastinum (mediastinitis). Emergent endoscopic removal is the standard of care for esophageal button battery impaction and should ideally occur within 2 hours. While awaiting endoscopy, honey (for children over 12 months) may be given per recent guidelines to create a viscous barrier and neutralize the alkaline environment, though this should not delay definitive removal. Activated charcoal is not effective for button batteries and may obscure endoscopic visualization. Observation is dangerous as tissue damage progresses rapidly. Ipecac-induced vomiting is contraindicated as it may cause the battery to lodge more firmly or cause aspiration. Batteries that have passed beyond the esophagus into the stomach may be observed with serial imaging unless the child is symptomatic.",
