    correctAnswer: 0,
    rationaleLong: "This presentation is classic for methemoglobinemia. The pathognomonic findings include: (1) chocolate-brown colored blood that does not turn red when exposed to oxygen, (2) a 'saturation gap' where pulse oximetry reads low (85%) despite a normal or elevated PaO2 on ABG (150 mmHg), and (3) clinical appearance better than expected for the SpO2 reading. Dapsone is a well-known cause of acquired methemoglobinemia. Methemoglobin is formed when the iron in hemoglobin is oxidized from the ferrous (Fe2+) to the ferric (Fe3+) state, rendering it unable to bind and transport oxygen. Standard pulse oximetry is unreliable in methemoglobinemia because it measures absorption at only two wavelengths (660nm and 940nm) and cannot distinguish methemoglobin from oxyhemoglobin or deoxyhemoglobin. As methemoglobin levels rise, SpO2 tends to plateau around 85% regardless of actual oxygen saturation. The treatment for symptomatic methemoglobinemia (levels above 20-30% or symptomatic at any level) is methylene blue 1-2 mg/kg IV over 5 minutes. Methylene blue acts as an electron carrier in the NADPH-methemoglobin reductase pathway, converting methemoglobin back to functional hemoglobin. Methylene blue is contraindicated in G6PD-deficient patients as they lack the NADPH needed for the reduction pathway.",
