    rationaleLong: "Sudden sniffing death syndrome (SSDS) is the primary mechanism of death from volatile substance abuse, particularly halogenated hydrocarbons like difluoroethane found in computer dusters. These substances sensitize the myocardium to catecholamines (epinephrine, norepinephrine), creating a state where even normal physiological catecholamine surges (from startle, exertion, or excitement) can trigger fatal ventricular fibrillation or ventricular tachycardia. This phenomenon can occur with the very first use and is responsible for approximately 22% of inhalant-related deaths. The mechanism involves the halogenated hydrocarbon blocking cardiac potassium channels and sensitizing beta-adrenergic receptors, lowering the threshold for catecholamine-induced dysrhythmias. Treatment of the resulting VF follows standard ACLS protocols, but it is important to note that exogenous epinephrine should be used with extreme caution (or avoided if possible) as it may worsen the catecholamine sensitivity. Beta-blockers may be considered for refractory dysrhythmias. While aspiration and hypoxia are potential complications, they are not the primary mechanism of sudden death. Methemoglobinemia is not typically associated with difluoroethane inhalation.",
