    rationaleLong: "This patient has bleeding from antiplatelet drug-induced platelet dysfunction rather than thrombocytopenia (his platelet count is normal). Dual antiplatelet therapy (clopidogrel + aspirin) irreversibly inhibits platelet function through different mechanisms: aspirin irreversibly inhibits cyclooxygenase-1 (COX-1) preventing thromboxane A2 formation, and clopidogrel irreversibly blocks the P2Y12 ADP receptor on platelets. Since these effects are irreversible, the affected platelets will remain dysfunctional for their entire lifespan (7-10 days). Desmopressin (DDAVP) at 0.3 mcg/kg IV enhances platelet adhesion by releasing von Willebrand factor (vWF) from endothelial cells, which promotes platelet aggregation through an alternative pathway independent of the COX-1 and P2Y12 mechanisms. DDAVP also releases factor VIII from storage sites. For severe or life-threatening bleeding, platelet transfusion may be necessary to provide new platelets with functional COX-1 and P2Y12 receptors. Note that platelets should be transfused at least 4-6 hours after the last clopidogrel dose, as circulating drug can inhibit transfused platelets. Tranexamic acid (an antifibrinolytic) can be used adjunctively but does not address platelet dysfunction. Protamine reverses heparin, not antiplatelet agents. Vitamin K reverses warfarin, not antiplatelet drugs.",
