    id: "en-tox-049", stem: "A 15-year-old female presents to the ED with her parents after drinking a 'detox tea' purchased online. She has nausea, vomiting, watery diarrhea, and abdominal pain. Her mother found the tea contains Amanita phalloides mushroom extract. Labs are currently normal. What should the emergency nurse anticipate regarding the clinical course?",
    options: ["A deceptive period of clinical improvement over 24-48 hours followed by potentially fatal hepatorenal failure requiring close monitoring and possible liver transplant", "Rapid onset of liver failure within 2 hours requiring immediate transplant listing", "Self-limiting GI symptoms resolving within 6 hours", "Isolated nephrotoxicity without liver involvement"],
    correctAnswer: 0,
    rationaleLong: "Amanita phalloides (death cap mushroom) poisoning follows a characteristic triphasic clinical course that is critical for the emergency nurse to understand. Phase I (GI phase, 6-24 hours post-ingestion): severe nausea, vomiting, watery/bloody diarrhea, abdominal cramping, and dehydration. The delayed onset of GI symptoms (6-12 hours after ingestion) distinguishes Amanita poisoning from other mushroom intoxications which typically present within 1-2 hours. Phase II (apparent recovery, 24-48 hours): deceptive clinical improvement where GI symptoms resolve and the patient may feel well. Labs may remain normal or show only mild elevations. This phase is dangerous because premature discharge can be fatal. Phase III (hepatorenal phase, 3-5 days): sudden onset of hepatic failure with markedly elevated transaminases, coagulopathy, jaundice, encephalopathy, and potentially renal failure. This phase can progress to fulminant hepatic failure requiring liver transplantation. Mortality without transplant is 10-30%. The toxin responsible is amatoxin (alpha-amanitin), which inhibits RNA polymerase II, halting protein synthesis in hepatocytes. Treatment includes aggressive IV fluids, N-acetylcysteine (which provides hepatoprotection), IV penicillin G or silibinin (milk thistle extract), and early hepatology consultation for transplant evaluation.",
