    id: "en-tox-050", stem: "A 40-year-old male presents to the ED after being bitten by a black widow spider on his forearm. He reports severe, spreading muscle pain and cramping in his abdomen, back, and extremities. Vital signs show HR 115, BP 185/110, and he is diaphoretic. What is the appropriate pharmacological management?",
    options: ["IV opioids for pain, benzodiazepines for muscle spasm, and consideration of Latrodectus antivenin for severe envenomation", "Topical corticosteroid cream and ice application to the bite", "Oral antihistamines and acetaminophen only", "IM epinephrine for suspected anaphylaxis"],
    correctAnswer: 0,
    rationaleLong: "Black widow spider (Latrodectus) envenomation causes a clinical syndrome called latrodectism, characterized by severe muscle spasm and pain that can mimic surgical emergencies such as appendicitis or myocardial infarction. The venom contains alpha-latrotoxin, which causes massive presynaptic release of neurotransmitters (acetylcholine, norepinephrine, GABA) at neuromuscular junctions and sympathetic nerve terminals. Clinical features include: severe muscle cramping that may generalize to the abdomen (rigid abdomen without rebound, known as 'boardlike abdomen'), back, and extremities; autonomic instability (hypertension, tachycardia, diaphoresis); and severe pain often described as waves of cramping. Management follows a stepwise approach: (1) IV opioids (morphine, fentanyl) for severe pain, (2) benzodiazepines (diazepam, lorazepam) for muscle spasm, (3) Latrodectus antivenin (Antivenin [Latrodectus mactans]) for severe envenomation refractory to pain and spasm management, patients with cardiac or respiratory compromise, or children/elderly. The antivenin is derived from horse serum and carries a risk of serum sickness and anaphylaxis. IV calcium gluconate was traditionally recommended but has been shown to be largely ineffective. This is not anaphylaxis (no urticaria, angioedema, or airway compromise), so epinephrine is not indicated.",
    learningObjective: "Manage black widow spider envenomation with analgesics, benzodiazepines, and antivenom for severe cases",
